sues of human rights and Buddhism are related. The question applies both to the violation of basic rights in Buddhist countries and to the defence of those rights which are well-grounded in Buddhist teachings.The volume provides academic essays that reflect this up to now rather neglected issue from the point of view of the three main Buddhist traditions, Theravada, Mahayana and Vajrayana. It provides multi-faceted and surprising insights into a rather unlikely relationship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman rights. 4aAsia. 4aBurma. 4aChina. 4aCultural Clash. 4aHuman Rights. 4aHuman. 4aIntercultural Studies. 4aReligion. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSociology of Religion. 4aThailand. 4aTibet. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aBurma.  aChina.  aCultural Clash.  aHuman Rights.  aHuman.  aIntercultural Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aSociology of Religion.  aThailand.  aTibet.1 aBrox, Trine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleming, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Alfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinert, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinert, Carmen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoloff, Carola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRömer, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt-Glintzer, Helwig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt-Leukel, Perry, econtr